---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Start A Puzzle Swap | Austin Puzzle Exchange"
  description="Practical guide to launching and maintaining a community puzzle exchange location."
>
  <section class="container page-intro reveal-on-scroll">
    <p class="eyebrow">Host Guide</p>
    <h1>How To Start and Host Your Own Puzzle Exchange</h1>
    <p>This guide combines local experience with community-library best practices. Content is paraphrased and adapted for Austin hosts.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="container section-stack">
    <article class="glass-card prose-block reveal-on-scroll">
      <h2>1. Pick a Visible, Easy-To-Access Location</h2>
      <p>Choose a spot people naturally pass by and can approach safely. If your home is not ideal, partner with a school, church, or neighborhood center.</p>
      <p>Before installation, check local rules (city, HOA, property owner) so your project stays welcome long term.</p>

      <h2>2. Use a Box Sized for Puzzle Reality</h2>
      <p>Puzzle boxes are bulkier than books, so storage volume matters. Aim for a weather-resistant box with enough depth for stacked puzzle cartons and bins.</p>
      <p>A practical starter target is around 17" wide x 20" tall x 12" deep minimum interior, then go larger when possible.</p>

      <h2>3. Build for Weather and Durability</h2>
      <p>Use exterior-rated paint and a protective top coat. Seal seams and keep shelves off the bottom floor where moisture can collect.</p>
      <p>If post-mounting, use safe digging practices and sturdy anchoring. In no-dig settings, heavy planters or weighted bases can work.</p>

      <h2>4. Launch with Enough Inventory</h2>
      <p>Seed the first wave with roughly 15-25 puzzles so early visitors find variety. It is normal for outbound borrowing to outpace donations at first.</p>
      <p>Bag loose pieces inside each box when possible and add clear condition labels to reduce frustration.</p>

      <h2>5. Make a Community-Friendly Opening</h2>
      <p>Announce launch day in neighborhood groups and invite puzzle drop-offs. Photos of setup and opening day help social sharing and local press coverage.</p>
      <p>Add your location to community maps/directories so new neighbors can discover you quickly.</p>

      <h2>6. Maintain a Simple Weekly Rhythm</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Quick check every few days at launch, then weekly once activity stabilizes.</li>
        <li>Retire heavily damaged puzzles or boxes with too many missing pieces.</li>
        <li>Remove unrelated donations (books, random items) to keep puzzle capacity available.</li>
        <li>Keep a small “lost pieces” container and spare bags/rubber bands on site.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>7. Optional Upgrades That Work</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Guest notebook for swap notes and community messages.</li>
        <li>Box stamp or label to identify puzzles from your exchange.</li>
        <li>Host QR code linking to your location page and social channels.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Starter Checklist</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Location chosen and permissions confirmed.</li>
        <li>Weather-resistant box installed and sealed.</li>
        <li>Starter inventory, bags, and labels prepared.</li>
        <li>Launch post and map listing published.</li>
        <li>Ongoing cleanup/restock routine scheduled.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="button-row">
        <a class="button" href="/about#contact">Volunteer Your Location</a>
        <a class="button button--secondary" href="/locations">See Existing Austin Locations</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="container section-stack">
    <article class="glass-card prose-block reveal-on-scroll">
      <h2>Further Resources</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://littlefreelibrary.org/start/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Little Free Library: Start your own library</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://littlefreelibrary.org/map/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Little Free Library: Community map model</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.geocaching.com/play" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Geocaching basics for optional discovery upgrades</a></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="meta-note">This page is adapted from community swap best practices, Austin operational experience, and your uploaded Ambassador guide. All wording here is newly written and paraphrased.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
